			    STPJS 361</div>
  <p class="std">There is one God, one Father, one Jesus, one hope of our calling, one baptism.<span class="footRef">1</span> * * * Many talk
  of baptism not being essential to salvation; but this kind of teaching would lay the foundation of
  their damnation.<span class="footRef">2</span> I have the truth, and am at the defiance of the world to contradict me, if they can.</p>
  <p class="std">I have now preached a little Latin, a little Hebrew, Greek, and German; and I have fulfilled all.
  I am not so big a fool as many have taken me to be. The Germans know that I read the German
  correctly.</p>
  <div class="topic">A Call to Repentance</div>
  <p class="std">Hear it, all ye ends of the earth<span class="footRef">3</span>&mdash;all ye priests, all ye sinners, and all men. Repent!  repent! 
  Obey the Gospel. Turn to God;<span class="footRef">4</span> for your religion won&rsquo;t save you, and you will be damned. I do not
  say how long. There have been remarks made concerning all men being redeemed<span class="footRef">5</span> from hell; but
  I say that those who sin against the Holy Ghost cannot be forgiven in this world or in the world to
  come;<span class="footRef">6</span> they shall die the second death.<span class="footRef">7</span> Those who commit the unpardonable sin<span class="footRef">8</span> are doomed to
  Gnolom<span class="footRef">9</span>&mdash;to dwell in hell, worlds without end.<span class="footRef">10</span> As they concoct scenes of bloodshed in this world,
  so they shall rise to that resurrection which is as the lake of fire and brimstone.<span class="footRef">11</span> Some shall rise to
  the everlasting burnings of God;<span class="footRef">12</span> for God dwells in everlasting burnings,<span class="footRef">13</span> and some shall rise to
  the damnation of their own filthiness,<span class="footRef">14</span> which is as exquisite a torment<span class="footRef">15</span> as the lake of fire and
  brimstone.</p>
  <p class="std">I have intended my remarks for all, both rich and poor, bond and free,<span class="footRef">16</span> great and small. I have
  no enmity<span class="footRef">17</span> against any man. I love you all;<span class="footRef">18</span> but I hate some of your deeds.<span class="footRef">19</span> I am your best friend,
  and if persons miss their mark it is their own fault. If I reprove a man, and he hates me,<span class="footRef">20</span> he is a fool;
  for I love all men, especially these my brethren and sisters.<span class="footRef">21</span></p>
  <p class="std">I rejoice in hearing the testimony of my aged friends. You don&rsquo;t know me; you never knew my
  heart.<span class="footRef">22</span> No man knows my history. I cannot tell it: I shall never undertake it. I don&rsquo;t blame any one
  for not believing my history. If I had not experienced what I have, I could not have believed it
  myself. I never did harm any man<span class="footRef">23</span> since I was born in the world. My voice is always for peace.<span class="footRef">24</span></p>
  <p class="std">I cannot lie down until all my work is finished.<span class="footRef">25</span> I never</p>
